    </div>

    <div class="body">

      I am dismayed that this article repeatedly cites the Wal-Mart claim that the four locations will create 1200 retail jobs without also citing the opposition claim (and the result of numerous studies) indicating that 1.5 jobs are lost from small businesses closing once a new Wal-Mart opens for every job created by that same new Wal-Mart location. This is a shamefully unbalanced piece that fails to cite the empirical data cited by Wal-Mart opponents. There isn't even any mention of the massive sex discrimination case against Wal-Mart for which the Supreme Court decided class certification was not appropriate, without ruling on the underlying merits of the claims of scores of women who allege sex discrimination by Wal-Mart. <br />
<br />
I don't care about ad hominem attacks against Andy Shallal for the size of his house, I care about reporters sincerely making the effort to quote the empirical arguments of both sides of a contentious issue, statistics included.
